segments.text: Testing 1, 2, 3, 4.
Testing 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.
This is the 27th of March.
We're at 2909 Coronado.
And I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with James Ray.
And you are now Jim or James?
I go by Jim now.
Jim.
All right, class of?

To introduce yourself to this tape and to anyone that would listen to it or read the transcription, describe family background, where you grew up, what did mom and dad do, where did you go to high school?
Okay, I'll start with my mom because she also had a brother who was an Aggie.

And then my dad, who was an Aggie, my mom was born in Royce City, Texas, and when she was very young, she moved to Rockwall, where her father was the county sheriff, and he had been the city marshal in Royce City.
He became the sheriff of Rockwall County, which is the smallest county in the state, northeast of Houston, out beyond Garland.
I'm sorry, northeast of Dallas, out beyond Garland.

And that's where she grew up and when she was a teenager her mother died and then a few years later her father got ill and became incapacitated and so she moved to Longview to live with her mom's sister and it was there that she met my dad.
My mom's maiden name was Norma Macklin M-A-C-L-I-N and my father was Leonard Franklin Ray.
He was born in Longview as I was and he met mom at a church social at the First Baptist Church in Longview and

They married, and then I was born in 1941, went through elementary school at Judson Grove Independent School District, which is now a part of the Longview School District, and I went there through the seventh grade, and in the summer of 1954, we moved to Conroe.
At Judson, my dad had been the vocational ag teacher
In Conroe, he taught high school biology and my mom still lives in Conroe.
My dad passed away in 1992 and I came to Texas A&M from Conroe High School in September of 1959.
My dad was the class of 1938, my mom's brother
started to A&M in the early 40s, then he went off to war, went off to Europe, and then he came back and finished, I believe, I believe he's listed, his class year's listed as 47 or 48.
He's Robert Edwin Macklin, Jr., named after their dad.
Why did you attend A&M?
Well, with Uncle Bob and my dad both being Aggies, I didn't know there was any other place.
No, I had heard a lot about it.
And I guess when I was a kid growing up, I remember on Saturday afternoons when we'd be out.
This is back in the late 40s and early 50s.

you know, we'd be out doing chores, sometimes, you know, washing the car or detailing, cleaning it up, and the car radio would be on, and I remember Kern Tips doing the Southwest Conference play-by-play for, back then, I guess it was Humble Oil and Refining Company, and hearing a lot about the

the games and the different players and I was very active in athletics as a youngster, played football, basketball and baseball and I didn't have any idea whether or not I'd ever be a competitive collegiate athlete or not but A&M was always one of my favorites.
Did you come to visit A&M before you came up to?
I did.
My dad brought me over here and we visited with a cousin, Joe Dark, who was in one of the cadet corps dorms and we went up to see him and I don't remember, I remember that visit but

I was kind of almost somewhere between neutral and maybe slightly negatively impressed with the dorms because they were so stark and austere just concrete and of course that was way back in the days before that they'd done all the renovations that was probably sometime in the in the early to mid 50s.
Did you and your buddies at high school talk about
colleges and schools?
Oh yeah, as a matter of fact, several of the guys had nicknamed me Aggie.
So did you ever seriously think about going anywhere else?
Not really.
When a buddy and I went to take the, it wasn't the SATs, back then it was called the college board exams, we took them on the Rice campus.
And because there were three places that they would send the test scores at no additional cost, I had mine sent to Texas A&M, Baylor, and Rice.
And never heard from Baylor or Rice.
Of course, I just sent the test scores, never sent an application when I sent the application to Texas A&M.
And then...
went over to check and see if it was satisfactory and make sure the application had been accepted.
They had already indicated that if I wanted to come I was acceptable academically.
You got here in the fall of 59.
That's correct.
Did you go to fish camp?
I don't believe I went to fish camp that year.
I went

to fish camp as a counselor I believe in my junior and senior years but I don't believe I was one and I'm not really sure how folks were selected back then or whether you had to volunteer for it and I really wasn't that familiar with it.
So when you came to enroll it was to begin classes.
Describe that trip over
mom and dad brought you in the car, and what did you bring with you, and so forth.
Gee, that made such a, I don't remember the trip over.
I don't remember what I brought with me.
Did you have a footlocker yet?
Probably so, either a footlocker or some kind of a suitcase.
It might have just been a few packing boxes.

to move in a few things but I probably traveled pretty lightly anyway knowing that there would be uniforms to wear and so I probably just had maybe some Sunday clothes to wear to church if that was permitted and I didn't even know and not very many civilian clothes and so just some basics and
Did mom and dad give you any advice or direction as you were getting ready for them to go home?
Not that I recall.
I don't have much of a remembrance until the

the initial meeting, the first, I guess I got there on a day, the sophomores must have been in a meeting somewhere when I arrived because it seemed like it was either a junior or a senior, kind of welcomed me and got me in a room and told me when the first fish meeting was gonna be.
How did you get, you and your outfit, how did that pair up?
How did you get assigned an outfit?
I really don't know.
When I got there and checked in, they told me I was going to be in Squadron 9 because I had requested an Air Force as opposed to an Army unit.
Even then, I knew I wanted to apply for pilot training.
Where was Squadron 9?
It was located in dorm 12.
I believe that's called Ute Hall, if I'm not mistaken.
It was right adjacent to Duncan Dining Hall, so it was the most southerly of the dorms.
And of course, we were... Did that outfit have a nickname?
It was called Hellcat 9.
and our group still refers to it.
In fact, although we were always Hellcat 9, it was an outfit that had just been reconstituted or created from seems like Squadron 5 and
I can't remember where the leadership cadre came.
I know some of them came from squadron five and it was one I guess that had been had been enacted for a while because of the fluctuation in the student population.
Anyway they reactivated it that year and we had had new leadership.
So there's a senior or junior who takes you to your room?
As I recall

That's the way it was and it was pretty pleasant the first, I'd say the first half of the first day because I remember getting in my room and having a chance to get pretty well established in the room before the first fish meeting and the first sophomores came in.
Describe that room.
It was a little, let me see.
When you open the door and there's a very, a fairly narrow hallway into a single room.
When you close the door, then you made room for the two closet doors to open from on either side of you.
And then on one side of the room was a metal iron bunk bed, double bunk.
And that was on the right hand side.
On the left hand side was a lavatory and a mirror.
Trying to remember if there were two of those or just one.
I guess you and your fish buddy, your fish old lady had to share those as I recall.
I'm just trying to visualize it.
And then just beyond the

the bunk in the corner there was a single window in the middle of the room and on either side of the window with the backs to the walls were the two study desks and so if you were both studying at the same time you sat back to back and then above the study desk was one or two shelves where you put your study books.
It was pretty austere, it was concrete
There was waxed concrete, if you can imagine that.
Fourth floor?
No, I was on the first floor.
How did you get that?
Well, there were two squadrons there, and Squadron 10 was up above us.
They had the third and fourth floors, and Squadron 9 was on the first and second floors, and they had us interspersed.
with all the other upperclassmen.
I know right opposite us were two sophomores.
To our right were two sophomores.
To our left were two juniors.
When you arrived, did you know much Aggie lingo and traditions and all that?
Not really.
Of course, I knew the spirit of Aggieland and the Aggie war hymn just from having attended a few football games with my dad and
and some friends but didn't know all of the lingo that you learned.
Did you know what to expect those first few days and nights?
Not really.
I think my dad had kind of dropped some hints that it would be military but that didn't bother me and really I was not as put off by
a lot of the early regimentation as some folks were.
In fact, we had a couple of guys in our outfit that didn't last more than a day or two.
And in fact, one of my buddies from Conroe, I won't mention his name, but he came and was in an army unit and he was there maybe three or four weeks.
And I remember my dad calling me one time saying that he and Mr. So-and-so were coming over to visit him and try to see what the problem was.
And the problem was he just didn't like the regimentation and the toughening process.
And so I think he quit and went to Baylor.
You said it was for a few hours it was pleasant and then here came the sophomores.
Describe all of that routine.
Well, they had a fish meeting and when we all fell out to go to the meeting, they lined us up on the second floor along the wall and
We learned how to stand at attention and hit a brace, chin tucked in, lots of wrinkles and all of that.
Although that part was conducted by the juniors and then the squadron commander who was John Lister
came out and gave us a pep talk, and that was the first warning we had that the sophomores were going to be taking up our training.
And there were a couple of sophomores present then, but it was mostly, it was the squadron, the commander and his executive officer, and then the first sergeant, Vernon Yotta,
And they are the ones who gave us the first orientation.
And the one or two sophomores that they had allowed at that first meeting were the ones that had been lining us up.
I guess that was the last of what you might call instructive
attitude.
From that time on it was a demanding attitude.

You know, you will do this, you will learn this, you will say, and it's when you learn to say yes sir, no sir, and sir not being informed to the highest degree of accuracy, I state to articulate in fear I may deviate from the true course of rectitude, in short term a very dumb fish, and do not know sir.
I said that often enough that I still remember it.
That's without any premeditated practice at all.
It's just right off the top.
When did you get your uniforms?
That is not real clear.
I remember you know going and having them issued.
I would guess it was either that same day that afternoon.
Where?
There used to be a wooden building down behind dorm one which was the
core headquarters, down at the end of the core quadrangle as you know where the new arches and all that entryway is now.
Of course at that end is where dorm one on the east side and dorms two on the west side and then dorm one runs north and south

and dorm two runs east and west and kind of offset from that on the street was a wooden building that housed a tailor shop and it was like a quartermaster actually it was an outlet for a cleaning and laundry service but on that occasion that was used as kind of the distribution point for
a lot of the uniforms.
Now that's where we went, all the Air Force people.
I don't know if the other cadets from other places went other places or not, but that's where we went.
That building also at that time housed the singing cadets.
Well, I say it did.
My memory's not clear whether that was my fish year or if that evolved during one of the subsequent years, but I know the singing cadets also occupied that building for a while.
Your uniforms, were these new or were they used?
They had been used before.
I don't remember specifically.
Occasionally guys would get some new ones, but a lot of them had been used before and were handed down.
Did they fit well?
Not at first.
They tried to get fairly close, but I remember having to go over to Northgate
to get them tailored especially after you put on the uniforms for the first time and that was probably either that evening or the next morning.
You put the uniform on and then we fell out in formation and in addition to the drill and ceremonies there was a lot of critique about how you wear the uniform and how

neat and how tight or loose and just a lot of critique to make the uniforms look right and the thing about that to me was I just assumed that everything that was happening even though it was a little harsh and a little strenuous at times I just figured that was normal for the military so I just adapted to it didn't complain about it and I figured it was you know when they

He told me how to straighten your gig line and how to tuck your shirt tail in and even things like, especially when you're getting ready for a graded review or march by, how at a certain point all the guys kind of turned inward, unzipped their fly, reached in, pulled the shirt tails down to tighten them

With your belt buckles tightened so the shirts would stay down and there wouldn't be any creases or wrinkles around your middle, you'd reach in and pull your shirt tails down and then zip your fly up and everybody turned back in formation as a little technique for getting a little bit better grade when you did your graded march-bys.
That's the first time I'd ever had that happen.
And it made an impression, but at the same time, I understood why and I went along with it.
When did your official lady arrive?
Probably that same afternoon.
Earl Henderson was my official lady from Houston.
He was Houston Spring Branch.
Did you all become fast friends?
We did.
We got along very well that year.
Although the second year,
Because his major and my major were different, we got other roommates.
We were just together the first year.
And the first semester, we lived in dorm 12.
And then there was some kind of a renovation project.
And I don't remember what they did,

it really didn't materially affect the rooms that much but there's some kind of renovation to the to the building itself and so our second freshman semester we moved over to the to dorm seven on the opposite side of the middle of the quadrangle on the opposite side and uh but same roommate same outfit yes and same routine same routine right
Now, I presume there were two or three days before classes started.
What all was done to whip you all into shape and to get you ready to be real members of the Corps?
How did they do that?
Well, I just remember spending a lot of time on the sidewalks and the quadrangle

over there on the west side of Duncan between Duncan and dorm 12 and then and then marching out on the the wide concrete in front of Duncan dining hall and uh occasionally and and there were a lot of other outfits were out there and I remember the uh just learning how to march and step to a cadence and uh and Jody calls and uh and uh
Every once in a while, if you messed up, a sophomore would take you out and give you some one-on-one drill and say, no, the other left.
And teaching you how to keep your elbows straight and cup your hands and everything to look military when you marched.
And to me, it was just something to learn.
I didn't object to it.
A lot of guys even the ones that stayed and made it all the way through complained a lot about how tough everything was and I just kind of shrugged it off and went along with it.
Of course I got my share of chewing out so if I did a misstep or did a right face when everybody else did a left face.

I just took it as a learning experience and went on of course I had been a competitive athlete so I was used to coaches you know sometimes I won't say yelling at you because that sometimes especially in modern day carries the wrong context but yeah there was a lot of yelling at you but I took it as being instructive and motivational and stressing the importance of you know if you screw up you make the outfit look bad
and so I really never had any problem adapting to it.

I never had any sense or thought of quitting or going home or complaining although there were a few times when some sophomores were leaning on us or some of our fish buddies so heavily that we retaliated and that was not only to me that was more good bull than it was

extreme frustration but I was always adventurous enough that if somebody was being harassed and needed some help I'd usually try to try to help them out and like the times where we water ballooned the guys right across the hall from us and another time when we babble bombed another guy from another outfit who had been harassing the fish unmercifully in fact unreasonably
describe the Babel bombing as y'all did?

Well let me do the water balloon first because that one happened first and I think getting away with that one kind of gave us the courage to try the other one later but Tommy Dabney and Jack Mahan live right across the hall from us and
I want to say Alton McGee and Grubby Heron were sophomores that lived to our right.
Now our room, our window faced Duncan.
So we were on the east side of the dorm and Tommy Dabney and Jack Mahan were on the west side right opposite us.
And they had been leaning pretty heavily on some of the fish and some of the guys were really, really frustrated.
So we decided, and they had gotten on our case harder than we thought was reasonable on several occasions.
And so we decided, as a matter of fact, we went up to one of the juniors.
His name is Billy Sewell from Waco.
And we asked for kind of a timeout or an academic situation to complain.
There were rules for, you know, venting grievances or requesting academic help or things like that.
where you could relax a little more and talk more frankly than you could normally on a day to day basis.
Billy Sewell had always seemed pretty reasonable and always had kind of a twinkle in his eye and yet he was sharp, he was gung ho.

but we figured that he was one of the juniors we could trust so I went with someone else I don't remember who it was it was probably Earl and we asked him we told him the kind of behavior and irrational exuberance as Alan Greenspan would put it that they were experiencing and that
we thought that was unreasonable and we asked if there was anything that the upperclassmen could do to rein that in and he kind of hemmed and hawed and well he was very

candid with us but it was kind of evasive as to what upperclassmen could do to solve that and he said that's part of the system you kind of have to go along with it to the extent that it's reasonable even if they're a little out of line and so we reiterated that we thought some things were

unreasonable and as we told him some of these things he kind of nodded didn't comment and we said uh well look if the uh if the upperclassmen can't do anything about it if we uh if we retaliated by babo bombing or water ballooning or or uh

say putting chickens in their room on the weekend when they're going to be gone for a couple of days which we'd heard these stories around about how other fish getting frustrated had retaliated and we asked him you know if uh... if we would be in trouble or really bad trouble uh... you know to the point where we might get kicked out of the outfit or kicked out of school if we retaliated and got them to be
and just sent them a signal that they were out of line.
He thought about it for a minute, and all he said was, not if you don't get caught.
And I guess he probably remembered his fish year and how frustrating sometimes things can get.
So we took that as our signal to go, but don't get caught.
So we picked the night.
I don't remember if it was the same night or...
